<b>Data-oriented parsing</b> (<b>DOP</b>, also <b>data-oriented processing</b>) is a <link>
probabilistic</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../716/18020716.xml">
grammar formalism</link> in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../561/5561.xml">
computational linguistics</link>. DOP was conceived by <physical_entity wordnetid="100001930" confidence="0.8">
<person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.8">
<causal_agent wordnetid="100007347" confidence="0.8">
<academician wordnetid="109759069" confidence="0.8">
<adult wordnetid="109605289" confidence="0.8">
<professional wordnetid="110480253" confidence="0.8">
<educator wordnetid="110045713" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../197/1569197.xml">
Remko Scha</link></educator>
</professional>
</adult>
</academician>
</causal_agent>
</person>
</physical_entity>
 in 1990 with the aim of developing a <link>
performance</link>-oriented grammar framework. Unlike other probabilistic formalisms, DOP takes into account all subtrees contained in a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../417/3732417.xml">
treebank</link> rather than being restricted to, for example, 2-level subtrees (like <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../329/299329.xml">
PCFGs</link>).<p>

Several variants of DOP have been developed. The initial version was based on <link>
tree-substitution grammar</link>, while more recently, DOP has been combined with <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../408/254408.xml">
lexical-functional grammar</link> (LFG). The resulting DOP-LFG finds an application in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../980/19980.xml">
machine translation</link>.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref></p>

